Sure, here are some examples:

1. *Suze* mi se same cede od radosti. (Tears *stream* down my face from joy.)
2. Stisla je zube i zadržala *suze*. (She clenched her teeth and held back her *tears*.)
3. Njegov glas me je rasplakao do *suza*. (His voice made me cry *tears*.)
4. Čim sam čula tu tužnu vest, počele su da mi teku *suze*. (As soon as I heard that sad news, *tears* started flowing down my face.)
5. *Suze* su joj se slivale niz obraze dok je pričala o svojoj baki. (*Tears* were rolling down her cheeks as she talked about her grandmother.)
6. Pokušala je da sakrije *suze*, ali joj nije uspelo. (She tried to hide her *tears*, but she couldn't.)
7. Nije mi jasno zašto ljudi ne pokazuju *suze* kada su tužni. (I don't understand why people don't show *tears* when they're sad.)
8. Njen glas je bio slomljen, a oči pune *suza*. (Her voice was broken, and her eyes were full of *tears*.)
9. Gledao je u nju dok su joj se *suze* slivale niz lice. (He watched her as *tears* rolled down her face.)
10. Posle dugog plakanja, ostale su samo *suze*. (After a long cry, only *tears* remained.)

Note: In Serbian, the word "suze" can mean both "tears" and "weeping".